Build a Node JS with MongoDB Application with Docker Compose
Tutorial

Build a Node JS with MongoDB Application with Docker Compose

5 steps

In this tutorial, we will be building a Node.js with MongoDB to perform CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations with Docker Compose. By the end of this tutorial, you will have a fully functional RESTful API CRUD application that’s containerised using Docker and tested with Postman.

There’s a lot to unpack in this tutorial, let’s begin! 🐳
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Complete the Basic DevOps with Docker Module

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Build a CRUD Application with Node.js and MongoDB
  • Use Docker Compose to run multiple services
  • Use Postman to invoke API calls for CRUD functionalities

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: Project Setup

    We will first initialise the project by running the following command. Ensure that you are under the root directory!

    mkdir docker_rest_api && cd docker_rest_api && npm init -y

    Next, navigate to the newly created folder and open the folder on your IDE! We will then install the necessary dependencies required to run the application! 

    npm install express body-parser mongodb mongoose

    These libraries collectively form the backbone of many backend applications. Express handles routes and middleware with efficiency, streamlining the request-response cycle. Body-parser, integrated into newer versions of Express, deciphers incoming request data, making it readily accessible for further processing.

    Mongodb establishes a direct connection from a Node.js application to a MongoDB database, enabling seamless data storage and retrieval. Lastly, mongoose adds structure to MongoDB collections by defining schemas, simplifying database interactions and ensuring data consistency.

    With the dependencies installed, we will next transition to our database setup!

    Database Setup

    Under the docker_rest_api directory, create a new file titled db.js.

    Next, copy the following code snippet and paste it into db.js!

    //Code to connect Express Application with MongoDB
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const connectDB = async () => {
 try {
  await mongoose.connect(
   "mongodb://root:example@db:27017",
   { useNewUrlParser: true },
   { useUnifiedTopology: true }
  );
  console.log("MongoDB Connected!");
 } catch (error) {
  console.log(error.message);
  process.exit(1);
 }
};

module.exports = connectDB;
    JavaScript

    In this code snippet, we will first import the mongoose library and next define an asynchronous function connectDB.

    In this asynchronous function, we will attempt to connect to MongoDB using our credentials. On successful connection, a success message is logged, else if the connection fails, an error message is logged and the process exits!

    With our database configured, in the next step, we will begin populating the models and schemas for our CRUD application!

    You can refer to Expected Output to view how package.json should be configured.

    Expected Output

  • Step 2: Create Schema

    In this step, we will define the models and schemas for our CRUD application. We will be setting up a user collection and will populate MongoDB with this user collection based on the schema that we have defined!

    To begin, create a new file titled user.js under the docker_rest_api directory.

    Next, copy the following code snippet and paste it into user.js.

    const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
 name: {
  type: String,
  required: true,
 },

 role: {
  type: String,
  required: true,
 },
});

const User = mongoose.model("User", userSchema);

module.exports = User;
    JavaScript

    In this code snippet, we first create a new schema titled userSchema with mandatory fields of name and role that are of type string. Using this schema, we next create a User model.

    This model would represent a user collection in our MongoDB database, allowing for CRUD operations on user data!

    To find out more about what schemas are in MongoDB, you can head over here!

    With our schema and user collection, we are now ready to build the application routes in the next step facilitating the CRUD functionalities in our application!

  • Step 3: Build Application Routes

    In this step, we will be building the application routes to enable CRUD functionalities in our application!

    To begin, create a new file titled app.js under the docker_rest_api directory.

    Next, copy the following code snippet and paste it into app.js.

    const express = require("express");
const connectDB = require("./db");
const User = require("./user");

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

connectDB();

// Create a new User
app.post("/users", async (req, res) => {
 try {
  const { name, role } = req.body;
  const user = new User({ name, role });
  await user.save();
  res.json({ success: true });
 } catch (error) {
  res.status(500).send(error.message);
 }
});

// Retrieves all users
app.get("/users", async (req, res) => {
 try {
  const users = await User.find();
  res.json(users);
 } catch (error) {
  res.status(500).send(error.message);
 }
});

// Update a user
app.put("/users/:id", async (req, res) => {
 try {
  const user = await User.findByIdAndUpdate(req.params.id, req.body, {
   new: true,
  });
  if (!user) throw new Error("User not found");
  res.json({ success: true });
 } catch (error) {
  res.status(500).send(error.message);
 }
});

// Delete a user
app.delete("/users/:id", async (req, res) => {
 try {
  const user = await User.findByIdAndDelete(req.params.id);
  if (!user) throw new Error("User not found");
  res.json({ success: true });
 } catch (error) {
  res.status(500).send(error.message);
 }
});

const port = 5000;

app.listen(port, () => {
 console.log("API server started on port 5000");
});
    JavaScript

    Code Breakdown

    In this code snippet, we will first initialize an Express application and connect our application to MongoDB using the asynchronous function connectDB from db.js!

    With the application connected to the database, we will next define the following routes for CRUD operations:

    • Create - POST route to /users creates a new user with the name and role fields parsed in from the request body
    • Read - GET route to /users fetches all users from the database
    • Update - PUT route to /users/:id updates a user’s data based on their ID
    • Delete - DELETE route to /users/:id removes a user from the database by ID

    The application listens on port 5000 and logs a message to the console when it’s successfully booted up!

    In the next step, we will focus on creating the Dockerfile and Docker Compose file enabling us to containerise our application.

  • Step 4: Create Dockerfile and Docker Compose File

    In this step, we will be creating 2 files namely - Dockerfile and docker-compose.yml.

    The Dockerfile will contain the series of instructions required to create a Docker image representing our application. The docker-compose.yml file on the other hand allows us to define and run multi-container Docker applications and in this instance, we will setup the application and MongoDB.

    With Docker Compose, we are able to define all of our required application services in a single file, allowing the overall deployment process more efficient and seamless!

    We will first create the Dockerfile! To do so, create a new file under the root directory titled Dockerfile!

    Next, copy the following code snippet and paste it into your newly created Dockerfile!

    FROM node:16-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY . /app
RUN npm install
EXPOSE 5000
CMD ["npm", "start"]
    Docker

    In our Dockerfile, we first use a lightweight Node.js image. Next, we set the working directory of the Docker container to be /app. Next, we copy all our existing files from the current directory to the /app directory in the container.

    We then install the required dependencies and expose port 5000. Lastly, we run the command npm start when the Docker container starts.

    Up next, we will create the docker-compose.yml file! To do so, create a new file under the root directory titled docker-compose.yml.

    Next, copy the following code snippet and paste it into your newly created docker-compose.yml file.

    version: "3.8"
services:
 db:
  image: mongo:latest
  restart: always
  environment:
   MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME: root
   MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD: example
  ports:
   - 27017:27017
  volumes:
   - mongo-data:/data/db

 app:
  build: .
  restart: always
  ports:
   - "5000:5000"
  depends_on:
   - db
volumes:
 mongo-data:
    YAML

    In our docker-compose.yml file, we have defined the following services:

    1. db - This represents the MongoDB container where we defined the database login credentials, paired with a port mapped to 27017.
    2. app - This represents the Node.js container built from our previously defined Dockerfile with a port mapping of 5000. Also, the app service will only start after the db using the depends_on flag.

    With the Dockerfile and docker-compose.yml defined, we are now ready to run the application using Docker Compose in the next step!

  • Step 5: Run Application

    In this step, we will be running our application using Docker Compose and test its CRUD operations using Postman.

    To begin, run the following command!

    docker compose up -d

    Running this command will pull the MongoDB Docker image from the Docker Hub registry and next build the custom Docker image as defined in our Dockerfile. Lastly, it will instantiate the two services defined in our docker-compose.yml file as shown below.

    To verify that the Docker containers are instantiated, run the following command.

    docker ps

    You should observe that 2 Docker Containers are running!

    Interacting with Postman

    Next, we will be invoking an API request to create a new user and retrieving all users using Postman! To begin, head over to Postman and login to your Postman account. If you do not have an existing Postman account, proceed to create a new account!

    Next, navigate to the Workspaces tab and create a new collection where you should observe the following as shown below.

    Create a New User

    Next, we will be creating a new user and adding it to our MongoDB user collection!

    Proceed to input localhost:5000/users as the request URL. Next, under the body option, select JSON and proceed to copy the following to the request body.

    {
"name": "Tony",
"role": "Developer"
}
    JSON

    Next, click on “Send” and upon a successful POST request, here’s how your Postman request should look like!

    To verify if the user has been successfully populated into the MongoDB user collection, we will be performing 2 checks:

    1. Head over to localhost:5000/users to verify if user has been added
    2. Check MongoDB Docker container for newly created user in collection

    First, head over to localhost:5000/users and you should observe that the user has been successfully added as shown below! 

    Next, head over to your terminal and run the docker ps command. Running this command will list the running containers on our terminal as shown below.

    Next, proceed to run the following command.

    docker exec -it  mongosh -u "root" -p "example"

    You should observe the following after running the command!

    We are now able to run commands inside our MongoDB Docker container! To verify that our user is added to the user collection, proceed to run the following command.

    db.users.find().pretty()
    MongoDB

    You should observe that the user has been successfully added to the user collection as shown below!

    Kudos 🎉🎉🎉, we have successfully built a multi-container CRUD application using Docker Compose! This is a significant achievement and do give yourselves a pat on the back!
